history.content: Probably not but it is completely at the discretion of the faculty member teaching the course.
If you want to suffer less in 189 because of a lack of pre-reqs, I would HIGHLY recommend being familiar with vector calculus in 53.

children.subject:
+1

If you haven't taken 53, but know it well enough, then that would be different.

However, if your plan is to "get it on the fly" as it comes in 189, then you are really doing yourself a disservice. The obvious one is when the vector calculus is the part you should know and the new topic is what you should spend time digesting; this is true for the homework and programming assignments. This course also does very little hand holding and there are topics in that course that will make so much more sense if you equip yourself with the necessary and recommended prerequisite courses. In some ways, that contributes to the mostly negative reputation of the course; that is, people going in unprepared.

I don't mean to be rude, but if you are at the point in your courses where you haven't taken math 53 yet, you probably shouldn't take 189. Do yourself the favor of allowing your brain to have a chance of absorbing the material rather than checking off a box of, "Yes, I've taken a ML class".
